<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-appendix">
  <title>Appendix</title>

  <section xml:id="appendix-writing">
    <title>Mathematical writing</title>
    
    <introduction>
      <aside xml:id="aside-su-articles">
        <p>
          A link to a nice relevant three-page article by Francis Su:
        </p>
        <p>
          <url href="https://math.hmc.edu/su/wp-content/uploads/sites/10/2020/06/Writing-Math-Well-HMC-Math.pdf">Writing Mathematics Well</url>
        </p>
        <p>
          and a one-page summary:
        </p>
        <p>
          <url href="https://faculty.math.illinois.edu/~notlaw/Su-Guidelines_for_Good_Mathematical_Writing.pdf">Some Guidelines for Good Mathematical Writing</url>
        </p>
      </aside>
    </introduction>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-audience">
      <title>Audience</title>
      <p>
        In all of the writing you do for a course based on this text, take your
        audience to be your fellow classmates. That will determine the amount
        of detail you need to include&#8212;do not skip important details, and
        do not include details that are not essential.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-sentences">
      <title>Sentences!</title>
      <p>
        The most important rule is that your writing should consist solely of
        complete sentences. A sentence starts with a capital letter and ends
        with a period. If you have a long calculation, you might want to
        neatly display it, but it should still be part of a sentence;
        something like this:
      </p>
      <p>
        Our result then follows from a calculation:
        <md>
          <mrow>\text{blah} \amp = \text{blah}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \text{blah}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp\ \ \vdots</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \text{blah}.</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-symbols">
      <title>Use of symbols</title>
      <p>
        For better readability, do not start a sentence with a mathematical
        symbol (i.e., a mathematical symbol does not count as a capital
        letter):
      </p>
      <p>
        <term>No:</term> <m>f</m> is injective but not surjective.
      </p>
      <p>
        <term>Yes:</term> The function <m>f</m> is injective but not surjective.
      </p>
      <p>
        In informal mathematical writing&#8212;the kind you might use on a
        blackboard or on scratch paper&#8212;it is common to use the symbols
        shown here.
      </p>
      <aside xml:id="aside-informal-symbols">
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\Rightarrow \amp:\quad \text{"implies"}</mrow>
            <mrow>\Leftrightarrow \amp:\quad \text{"if and only if"}</mrow>
            <mrow>\forall \amp:\quad \text{"for all"}</mrow>
            <mrow>\exists \amp:\quad \text{"there exists"}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </aside>
      <p>
        In your formal written work, e.g., homework assignments, do not use
        these. Instead, write out the words. It is slightly more work for you,
        but it makes life easier for your reader. Of course, you will need to
        use symbols in your writing&#8212;just do not use those listed in
        formal writing. On the other hand, here are some symbols from logic we
        encourage you to never use, even in informal work: <q><m>\land</m></q> for
        <q>and</q>, <q><m>\lor</m></q> for <q>or</q>, and <q><m>\sim</m></q> for
        <q>not</q>. Again, it is easier on your reader to use the word instead
        of these symbols.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-red-herrings">
      <title>Red herrings</title>
      <image source="redherring3.png" width="30%">
        <description>
          <p>A picture of a red herring.</p>
        </description>
      </image>
      <p>
        Whenever you finish a proof by contradiction and now have the ideas in
        front of you, ask yourself whether a straightforward proof (without
        contradiction) is at least as clear as the one you have given. If so,
        make the change. It makes for a less convoluted argument. Apply
        similar reasoning to any proof where you have replaced the statement
        of the result by its (logically equivalent) contrapositive (not
        <m>Q</m> implies <m>P</m>, rather than <m>P</m> implies <m>Q</m>).
      </p>
      <p>
        More generally, review your proofs to see if you have included
        irrelevant information.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-backwards-proof">
      <title>The <q>backwards</q> proof</title>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-backwards-1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>x \in \R</m>. Then <m>(x+1)^2 - (x-1)^2 = 4x</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <p>
        (Incorrect proof.) Calculate:
        <md>
          <mrow>(x+1)^2-(x-1)^2 \amp = 4x</mrow>
          <mrow>(x^2+2x+1)-(x^2-2x+1) \amp = 4x</mrow>
          <mrow>x^2+2x+1-x^2+2x-1 \amp = 4x</mrow>
          <mrow>4x \amp = 4x.</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <image source="warning.png" width="15%">
        <description><p>A warning symbol.</p></description>
      </image>
      <p>
        The problem with this <q>proof</q> is in its first line: it seems to
        assert as true exactly what it is trying to prove&#8212;circular
        reasoning. To make the mistake even more clear, consider the following
        false statement, which uses the same reasoning:
      </p>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-backwards-2">
        <statement>
          <p>
            In <m>\R</m>, we have <md>1 = 0.</md>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <p>
        (Incorrect proof.) Calculate:
        <md>
          <mrow>1 \amp = 0</mrow>
          <mrow>0\cdot 1 \amp = 0\cdot 0</mrow>
          <mrow>0 \amp = 0.</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        To fix the proof of the original theorem, one could just list the
        lines of the proof in reverse order&#8212;hence, the moniker
        <q>backwards</q>&#8212;starting with <m>4x=4x</m>. However, notice
        another flaw with the proof: by just listing these lines, we break the
        rule that a proof consists of sentences. Here is the correct form,
        fixing both problems:
      </p>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-backwards-3">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>x \in \R</m>. Then <m>(x+1)^2 - (x-1)^2 = 4x</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Calculate:
            <md>
              <mrow>(x+1)^2-(x-1)^2 \amp = (x^2+2x+1)-(x^2-2x+1)</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = x^2+2x+1-x^2+2x-1</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = 4x.</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-misc-writing">
      <title>Miscellaneous</title>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              To prove a statement is false, give a specific concrete
              counterexample. Try to find the simplest one. The counterexample
              is more convincing and easier on the reader than an abstract
              argument. Conversely, to prove a statement is true, an example,
              although sometimes helpful, is not a proof. You must show why the
              statement is true in all instances.
            </p>
            <aside xml:id="aside-counterexample">
              <title>Example</title>
              <p>
                <term>Statement:</term> <m>f(n) = n+2</m> is even for all
                <m>n \in \Z</m>.
              </p>
              <p>
                <term>Disproof:</term> Note that <m>f(1) = 3</m>, which is not
                even.
              </p>
              <p>
                <term>Statement:</term> <m>f(n) = n+2</m> is divisible by
                <m>7</m> for all <m>n \in \Z</m>.
              </p>
              <p>
                <term>False proof:</term> We have <m>f(12) = 14</m>, which is
                divisible by <m>7</m>.
              </p>
            </aside>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If you use the phrase <q>by definition</q> in your writing, make
              sure to be specific: by definition of what? For example, you
              might write <q>by definition of a Hausdorff space</q>. Using the
              phrase <q>by definition</q> in isolation is usually ambiguous,
              and if your reader cannot determine which definition you are
              referring to, then it is no help at all&#8212;everything in
              mathematics follows from the definitions!
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              When writing down a calculation, avoid crossing out terms (for
              example, when terms cancel in fractions or when they add up to
              zero). This type of bookkeeping is easy for the writer, who is
              crossing out sequentially, but is usually confusing for the
              reader, who sees all of the crosses at once.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-tex-pointers">
      <title><m>\LaTeX</m> pointers</title>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              When defining a function, use <c>\colon</c> rather than
              <c>:</c>, as in <c>f\colon X\to Y</c>. The latter symbol is
              regarded as an operator and is padded by unwanted spaces.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use the <m>\LaTeX</m> versions of the trig
              functions, e.g., <c>\cos(t), \tan(t)</c>, etc., rather than plain
              <c>cos(t), tan(t)</c>, etc. The same goes for logarithms:
              <c>\log(t), \ln(t)</c>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Add a little space before a differential, e.g., <c>\int x\,dx</c>,
              which gives <m>\int x\,dx</m> rather than <c>\int xdx</c>, which
              gives <m>\int xdx</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="appendix-templates">
    <title>Proof templates</title>

    <introduction>
      <aside xml:id="aside-blah-blah">
        <title>On <q>blah, blah, blah</q></title>
        <p>
          The <q>blah, blah, blah</q>s appearing in the template proofs below
          usually consist of two parts. The first part is automatic: you expand
          the statement of the theorem using relevant definitions so that the
          reader understands what you are trying to prove. The second is where
          the real math occurs. It often requires some insight and creativity.
        </p>
      </aside>

      <p>
        By convention, the proofs of certain types of statements are expected to
        have a certain structure. Here, we provide examples of some of these
        that are important for us. Deviating from these structures risks
        confusing your reader and, thus, usually entails the addition of a few
        words of guidance in your proof.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <subsection xml:id="appendix-sets">
      <title>Statements involving set containment</title>

      <definition xml:id="defn-subset">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be sets. Then <m>A</m> is a
            <term>subset</term> of <m>B</m>, denoted <m>A \subseteq B</m>, if
            <m>a \in A</m> implies <m>a \in B</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <definition xml:id="defn-set-equality">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be sets. Then these sets are
            <term>equal</term>, denoted <m>A = B</m>, if both
            <m>A \subseteq B</m> and <m>B \subseteq A</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <definition xml:id="defn-union-intersection">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be sets. Then the <term>union</term> of
            <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is
            <md>A \cup B := \left\{ x : x \in A \text{ or } x \in B \right\}.</md>
            In words, <m>x \in A \cup B</m> if <m>x</m> is in <m>A</m> or
            <m>x \in B</m>. The <term>intersection</term> of <m>A</m> and
            <m>B</m> is
            <md>A \cap B := \left\{ x : x \in A \text{ and } x \in B \right\}.</md>
            In words, <m>x \in A \cap B</m> if <m>x \in A</m> and
            <m>x \in B</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-subset-template">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be sets defined by
            <c>[some condition]</c>. Then <m>A \subseteq B</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Let <m>a \in A</m>. Then blah, blah, blah. Therefore,
            <m>a \in B</m>. It follows that <m>A \subseteq B</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-set-equality-template">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be sets defined by
            <c>[some condition]</c>. Then <m>A = B</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>a \in A</m>. Then blah, blah, blah. Therefore
            <m>a \in B</m>, too. Thus, <m>A \subseteq B</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            To show the opposite containment, suppose that <m>b \in B</m>.
            Then blah, blah, blah. Thus, <m>b \in A</m>. It follows that
            <m>B \subseteq A</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>

      <example xml:id="example-distributive">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m> be sets. Then
            <md>A \cap (B \cup C) = (A \cap B) \cup (A \cap C).</md>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Let <m>x \in A \cap (B \cup C)</m>. It follows that <m>x \in A</m>
            and <m>x \in B \cup C</m>. Since <m>x \in B \cup C</m>, we have
            that <m>x \in B</m> or <m>x \in C</m>. Consider the case where
            <m>x \in B</m>.
          </p>
          <aside xml:id="aside-example-distributive-note">
            <title>Note</title>
            <p>
              The second and third sentences unravel the relevant definitions,
              and should be automatic. The creativity&#8212;admittedly not
              much here&#8212;then starts.
            </p>
          </aside>
          <p>
            Then we have <m>x \in A</m> and <m>x \in B</m>, i.e.,
            <m>x \in A \cap B</m>. Hence, <m>x \in (A \cap B) \cup (A \cap
            C)</m>. Now assume that <m>x \in C</m>. Similar reasoning again
            shows that <m>x \in (A \cap B) \cup (A \cap C)</m>. We have shown
            that
            <md>A \cap (B \cup C) \subseteq (A \cap B) \cup (A \cap C).</md>
          </p>
          <p>
            For the opposite inclusion, suppose <m>x \in (A \cap B) \cup (A
            \cap C)</m>. It follows that <m>x \in A \cap B</m> or <m>x \in A
            \cap C</m>. Consider the first of these two cases: if <m>x \in A
            \cap B</m>, then <m>x \in A</m> and <m>x \in B</m>. Since <m>x \in
            B</m>, it follows that <m>x \in B \cup C</m>. So <m>x \in A</m>
            and <m>x \in B \cup C</m>, and therefore <m>x \in A \cap (B \cup
            C)</m>. The second case, where <m>x \in A \cap C</m>, is similar.
            Hence,
            <md>(A \cap B) \cup (A \cap C) \subseteq A \cap (B \cup C).</md>
            The result follows.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="appendix-functions">
      <title>Injectivity, surjectivity, bijectivity</title>

      <definition xml:id="defn-image-injective-surjective">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>f\colon A \to B</m> be a function. The <term>image</term>
            of <m>f</m> is the subset of <m>B</m> defined as follows:
            <md>\im(f) := \left\{ f(a) : a \in A \right\}.</md>
            The function <m>f</m> is <term>injective</term> if
            <m>f(x) = f(y)</m> only if <m>x = y</m>. The function <m>f</m> is
            <term>surjective</term> if <m>\im(f) = B</m>, i.e., if for each
            <m>b \in B</m>, there exists <m>a \in A</m> such that
            <m>f(a) = b</m>. The function <m>f</m> is
            <term>bijective</term> if it is injective and surjective.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-injective-template">
        <statement>
          <p>The function <m>f\colon A \to B</m> is injective.</p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Let <m>x, y \in A</m>, and suppose that <m>f(x) = f(y)</m>. Then
            blah, blah, blah. It follows that <m>x = y</m>. Hence, <m>f</m> is
            injective.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-surjective-template">
        <statement>
          <p>The function <m>f\colon A \to B</m> is surjective.</p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Let <m>b \in B</m>. Then blah, blah, blah. Thus, there exists
            <m>a \in A</m> such that <m>f(a) = b</m>. Hence, <m>f</m> is
            surjective.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-bijective-template">
        <statement>
          <p>The function <m>f\colon A \to B</m> is bijective.</p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <title>Alternative 1</title>
          <p>
            We first show that <m>f</m> is injective. [Follow the template
            above to show injectivity.] Next, we show <m>f</m> is surjective.
            [Follow the template above to show surjectivity.]
          </p>
        </proof>
        <proof>
          <title>Alternative 2</title>
          <p>
            Define <m>g\colon B \to A</m> as follows: blah, blah, blah. Note
            that <m>g \circ f = \mathrm{id}_A</m> since blah, blah, blah.
            Next, note that <m>f \circ g = \mathrm{id}_B</m> since blah, blah,
            blah.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>

      <example xml:id="example-bijective-2x">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>f\colon \R \to \R</m> be defined by <m>f(x) = 2x</m>. Then
            <m>f</m> is bijective.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To see <m>f</m> is injective, let <m>x, y \in \R</m> and suppose
            that <m>f(x) = f(y)</m>. Since <m>f(x) = f(y)</m>, we have that
            <m>2x = 2y</m>. Dividing by <m>2</m>, we see that <m>x = y</m>.
            Hence, <m>f</m> is injective.
          </p>
          <p>
            To see that <m>f</m> is surjective, let <m>z \in \R</m> (in the
            codomain). Then, in the domain, we have <m>z/2 \in \R</m>, and
            <m>f(z/2) = 2(z/2) = z</m>. Hence, <m>f</m> is surjective.
          </p>
          <p>
            Since <m>f</m> is injective and surjective, it is bijective.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>

      <example xml:id="example-not-bijective-xsquared">
        <title>Example 2</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>f\colon \R \to \R</m> be defined by <m>f(x) = x^2</m>.
            Then <m>f</m> is neither injective nor surjective.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To see that <m>f</m> is not injective, note that
            <m>f(-1) = f(1) = 1</m> even though <m>-1 \neq 1</m>. To see that
            <m>f</m> is not surjective, note that <m>-1</m> is not in the
            image of <m>f(x) = x^2</m> since <m>x^2 \geq 0</m> for all
            <m>x \in \R</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>

      <example xml:id="example-bijective-xsquared-nonneg">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>f\colon \R_{\geq 0} \to \R_{\geq 0}</m> be defined by
            <m>f(x) = x^2</m>. Then <m>f</m> is bijective. (Here,
            <m>\R_{\geq 0}</m> denotes the set of nonnegative numbers.)
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>Exercise.</p>
        </solution>
      </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="appendix-equivalence">
      <title>Equivalence relations</title>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-equivalence-template">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Define a relation <m>\sim</m> on a set <m>A</m> by blah, blah,
            blah. Then <m>\sim</m> is an equivalence relation.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            <term>Reflexivity.</term> For each <m>a \in A</m>, we have
            <m>a \sim a</m> since blah, blah, blah. Therefore, <m>\sim</m> is
            reflexive.
          </p>
          <p>
            <term>Symmetry.</term> Suppose that <m>a \sim b</m>. Then, blah,
            blah, blah. It follows that <m>b \sim a</m>. Therefore
            <m>\sim</m> is symmetric.
          </p>
          <p>
            <term>Transitivity.</term> Suppose that <m>a \sim b</m> and
            <m>b \sim c</m>. Since blah, blah, blah, it follows that
            <m>a \sim c</m>. Therefore, <m>\sim</m> is transitive.
          </p>
          <p>
            Since <m>\sim</m> is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive, it
            follows that <m>\sim</m> is an equivalence relation.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
    </subsection>

    <!-- <subsection xml:id="appendix-induction">
      <title>Induction</title>
      <p>
        See <xref ref="prop-induction-template"/> for an induction proof
        template.
      </p>
    </subsection> -->
  </section>
</chapter>
